<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
There are many things that affect aggro:<P>1. Your level relative to the mob<BR>2. Your health (if it is below 40%)<BR>3. The other people on the aggro list<BR>4. Proximity to the mob<BR>5. Whether you are sitting or standing<BR>6. Movement impedement spells (See 4)<P>The trick with tash is to know when to cast it.  On a mob like that you learn after one or 2 beatdowns when to cast tash  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">  A general rule for me on mobs like that is count to 10 slowly after the main tank has engaged then tash.  Be sure the main tank hold aggro for the whole time though, if the mob wanders around smacking people then do not tash until the main tank holds uninterrupted aggro for 10 full seconds.<P>Then modify your timing up or down depending on the response.  A perfect tash is when you tash the mob, it summons you and does not hit you.  You are right on the edge of getting aggro but not quite there  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>Regards,<P>--------------------<P><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=65288" TARGET=_blank>Sage Zanithar TideBreaker</A><BR>Phantasmist <BR>The Relentless, Cazic Thule
</FONT>
