<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
As a suggestion it's also worth getting into the habbit of doing a "tentative sit" using ctrl-s and keeping an eye on the mob; if it moves at all when you sit stand straight up using ctrl-s again. If you're quick it won't actually do anything more than turn towards you. Obviously this is less useful when mobs summon  <IMG SRC="biggrin.gif" border="0"><P>Depending on the situation it's also worth working close to the tanks; if you get agro it then doesn't have to move far to be able to bash you, and that makes it easier for people to regain agro since they don't have to spend a second or two figuring out that the mob's gone chanter-hunting, and that it's now "way over there somewhere"... Ping-pong should be played with a plastic ball, not MOBS. Again less of a concern for summoning mobs.<P>Since no one else has chimed in with a "I know it's based on mob hit points, 100% certain" I may as well add my own vote to this hypothesis; I have learned to wait a lot longer before tashing hp-heavy mobs than your normal trash.<P>A note on the slowing; I tend to find that unless you get a resist (resists seem to generate large amounts of hate, which kinda-makes sense), if you've tashed without trouble then you can slow and sit without trouble; slowing takes such a long time that the tanks will have outaggroed your new hate by the time it lands.<P>Core
</FONT>
