<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Sure is a lot of BS being thrown around here as if it is fact.  Some of you talk as if you know things as fact when you are really are just making an offbase assumption.<P>Here is one for example...<BR><I>The more swings you take the more the mob hates you even if you miss or do 1 damage its considered youre max possible damage. </I><P>This is total false logic.  I have no idea how people started thinking this crap but nobody ever seems to see the faulty logic behind it.  Statements like this come from people who do not understand that you need to know the INTENTION behind the system to understand a system.  <P>The INTENTION around the agro system is to determine who the mob should focus on based on how each player has EFFECTed the mob.  That quoted above statement says it does not matter how a player effects the mob, only that the player attempted to effect the mob.  In a real world battle, why would a warrior care how big the weapon is or how strong an attacker may be.   He would only care how much an attacker is hurting him.  If there are multiple attackers on a warrior and the bigger attacker with the powerful weapon is attampting to attack the warrior but can barely wield the weapon, the warrior is going to take out the attacker that is doing the most damage, and that wont be the clumsy big guy with the sharp weapon.  sharp weapon, big guy, or not, if you cant hit me, you cant hurt me.  You are a fly (a big fly) that I will swat later.<P>Equating this to a in-game model.  Your statement neglects weapon skill all together. There is weapon skill in-game for a reason.   If I hand a level 60 warrior a big, bad "uber" weapon that the warrior has zero skill in, I can garantee you that the warrior will be terrible at maintaining agro over time bacause the warriors damage output over time will serioursly suck.  Weapon skill, character level, and type of weapon, all calculate into a variating damage output.  It is damage output that must determine agro, because that is what follows the real-world intention.  Hell, that is why games of this nature have levels, skills(thak0), and weapon damage.  It symbolizes increasing damage output that comes from real-world increasing weapon skill.  That is what makes sense in-game.
</FONT>
