<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
The aggro on the Tash series was reduced because Furor of FoH was able to grab and keep aggro for an entire battle simply by wielding a weapon that proc'd Tash. In typical "tactic nerfing" fashion, Verant reduced aggro on Tash to "fix" the encounter. The fact it made our lives easier was the price they had to pay.  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P><I>Statements like this come from people who do not understand that you need to know the INTENTION behind the system to understand a system.</I><P>The trouble is that both the INTENTION behind the system and the IMPLEMENTATION of that system affect its behaviour. If the IMPLEMENTATION is shoddy or broken, the INTENTION doesn't matter. Ask any monk about Feign Death for a recent example.  <IMG SRC="frown.gif" border="0"><P>My understanding is that the hate generated by Tash is a % of the (remaining) HP of the mob. As others have pointed out, where you fall on the hate list is influenced by other factors (proximity, sitting, invulnerability, etc.) For example, I could Tash most Drolvargs in DL without attracting aggro. The exceptions were Raging and Ravishings. Once I gained a couple levels, Raging Drolvargs wouldn't aggro any longer. But those Ravishings still wouldn't leave me alone.<P>And yes, the "test sitting" is a great idea, especially if you are opposite the rogue. Sit, mob turns, STAB.  <IMG SRC="biggrin.gif" border="0"><P>--------------------<P>Luthian - 54th level Bossy Illusionist<BR>Xev
