<B> The trouble is that both the INTENTION behind the system and the IMPLEMENTATION of that system affect its behaviour. If the IMPLEMENTATION is shoddy or broken, the INTENTION doesn't matter. Ask any monk about Feign Death for a recent example. </B><P>No, you are still misunderstanding INTENTION.  It is not detailed list specifications of how something is supposed to work, look like, or be implemented.  It is just a basic general statement of what something is.  If I ask a monk what feign death is, they better tell me it is where you act like you are dead (because mobs dont attack the dead) and a mob may or may not believe it.  That is the INTENTION.  If they tell me that it does not work, they are full of it.  Just because it does not work for a particular instance, it does not mean that "feign death" overall does not work.  The INTENTION always matters in design.
