<I>No, you are still misunderstanding INTENTION. It is not detailed list specifications of how something is supposed to work, look like, or be implemented. It is just a basic general statement of what something is. If I ask a monk what feign death is, they better tell me it is where you act like you are dead (because mobs dont attack the dead) and a mob may or may not believe it. That is the INTENTION. If they tell me that it does not work, they are full of it. Just because it does not work for a particular instance, it does not mean that "feign death" overall does not work. The INTENTION always matters in design.</I><P>Trust me, I know what INTENTION is and why it is important in the design of a system. Since I write code for a living, I also understand how IMPLEMENTATION can subvert that design. The fact is that FD was broken due to a broken IMPLEMENTATION and thus didn't follow the INTENTION. You <B>didn't</B> lose aggro; you died instead.  <IMG SRC="eek.gif" border="0"> <P>The Tash series is INTENDED to reduce the mob's MR some amount and generates some hate as a result. This whole thread is about the IMPLEMENTATION of that INTENT and the amount of hate generated. This amount changed recently (and some suspect it has been changed BACK).<P>To put it without the shouting, the intent describes what should be and the implementation describes what is; they are often not the same and playing as if they were will often get you killed.<P>--------------------<P>Luthian - 54th level Bossy Illusionist<BR>Xev
